{
  "texts": [
    "where M BH is the mass of the black hole, and G and c are the gravitational constant and speed of light.",
    "This radius defines the event horizon of a (non-spinning) black hole.",
    "For a typical mass of M BH = 10 8 M, we have r g ∼ 3 × 10 8 km that corresponds to ∼ 2 AU, 10 -2 lt-days, or ∼ 10 -5 pc.",
    "In the perspective of microlensing applications, this should be compared to the typical Einstein radius of a microlens in the source plane (taken as the average from Mosquera and Kochanek 2011, see also Eq.",
    "Finally, another quantity of interest from general relativity typically associated with the inner edge of the disc is the radius of the innermost stable circular orbit of a photon, R ISCO = αr g, where α = 3 for a non-rotating black hole and 9/2 (1/2) for a maximally pro-(retro-) grade spinning one."
  ]
